{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626580"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:39:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:39:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17083"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17083"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69201"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9773"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17083"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54653"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5105"},{"type":"tags","id":"10106"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23174"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26655"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69201"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman with hypothyroidism is started on thyroid hormone replacement therapy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne such medication is liothyronine. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes liothyronine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroid stimulating hormone analogue","Thyroid hormone binding protein","Thyroid hormone receptor antagonist","Most active form of thyroid hormone","Inactive precursor of thyroxine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELiothyronine (T3) is the \u003Cstrong\u003Emost active form of thyroid hormone\u003C/strong\u003E. It is produced primarily through peripheral conversion of thyroxine (T4) by deiodinase enzymes. In peripheral tissues, type 1 and type 2 deiodinase enzymes remove an iodine atom from T4 to produce the active form T3, which has approximately four times the potency of T4 and a shorter half-life of one to two days compared to seven days for T4.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid stimulating hormone analogue\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because liothyronine is a thyroid hormone, not a pituitary hormone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid hormone binding protein\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because liothyronine is a hormone, not a transport protein like thyroid binding globulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid hormone receptor antagonist\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because liothyronine is an agonist that activates thyroid hormone receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInactive precursor of thyroxine\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because liothyronine is more active than thyroxine, not a precursor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiothyronine acts by entering cells and binding to nuclear thyroid hormone receptors, where it regulates gene transcription to influence metabolism, growth, and development. While most thyroid hormone is secreted as T4, approximately 20% of T3 is produced directly by the thyroid gland, with the remaining 80% produced by peripheral conversion of T4.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Liothyronine (T3) is the most potent thyroid hormone and is produced by peripheral conversion of thyroxine (T4).","Liothyronine has a shorter half-life and faster onset of action compared to thyroxine.","Liothyronine acts by binding to nuclear thyroid hormone receptors to regulate gene transcription."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54653"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17083"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54653"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T13:23:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T13:24:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9773"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69201"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms